==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hallow
<hw>Hal"low</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧l"l⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hallowed</conjf><pr>(-l⟦osl⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hallowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>halowen</ets>,
<ets>halwien</ets>, <ets>halgien</ets>, AS. <ets>h⟦amac⟧lgian</ets>, fr.
<ets>h⟦amac⟧lig</ets> holy. See <er>Holy</er>.]</ety> <def>To make holy;
to set apart for holy or religious use; to consecrate; to treat or keep
as sacred; to reverence.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hallowed</xex> be thy
name.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Matt. vi. 9.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hallow</qex> the Sabbath day, to do no work therein.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. xvii. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His secret altar touched with <qex>hallowed</qex> fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a larger sense . . . we can not <qex>hallow</qex> this ground
[Gettysburg].</q> <rj><qau>A. Lincoln.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hallowed</ent>⟦br⟧
